Title: The Completed Harmony: A Computational Pilot Study of Musical Encodings in Robert Fludd’s Monochordum Mundi
Author: Morgan H. Sherer\textsuperscript{1}
\textsuperscript{1}Independent Researcher, Seattle, Washington. Email: \href{mailto:Think.tattoo.viz@gmail.com}{Think.tattoo.viz@gmail.com}
Date: December 14, 2025
ArXiv Categories: Primary: physics.hist-ph (History and Philosophy of Physics); Cross-lists: cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.SD (Sound).
Keywords: Robert Fludd; Johannes Kepler; Optical Music Recognition; microtonality; history of physics; digital humanities.
Comments: 32 pages, 4 figures, 3 tables. Code and data available at: \href{https://github.com/mhsherer/harmonia-occulta}{github.com/mhsherer/harmonia-occulta} (Tag v1.0.0).
Abstract
The 17th-century dispute between Johannes Kepler and Robert Fludd is often framed as a binary clash between mathematical astronomy and hermetic mysticism. This paper presents a single-plate, single-text pilot study for Computational Antiquarianism, a methodology combining regression-based Optical Music Recognition (OMR) and statistical text analysis to recover latent models from historical artifacts. We extract a static harmonic framework from Fludd's Monochordum Mundi, identifying a specific interval at the Earth node that deviates from Pythagorean tuning by $>4\sigma$ relative to workshop noise. This interval (16:15) numerically aligns with the apsidal turning points of Kepler’s elliptical orbits described in Harmonices Mundi. A coincidence analysis suggests the probability of this match occurring by chance is $<0.5\%$. Furthermore, statistical analysis of pseudonymous Rosicrucian texts reveals a statistically significant over-representation of musical characters ($p < 0.001$, Odds Ratio 1.25). These findings suggest a unified cosmological model where Kepler provided the kinematic data and Fludd provided the discrete tuning reference. We propose this pipeline as a generalizable tool for retrieving quantitative models from early modern schematic art.
Plain-Language Summary
Note: This section summarizes the technical findings for interdisciplinary readers.
In simple terms, we treated a 400-year-old diagram of a cosmic monochord as a precise measuring instrument. We used computer vision to measure the spacing of the planetary notes, comparing them to a "noise" baseline derived from decorative columns in the same book. We found that while most notes followed standard tuning, the "Earth" note was compressed by almost a full semitone—exactly matching the mathematical value Kepler assigned to Earth's orbital speed. Finally, we counted letter frequencies in a related Rosicrucian text and found a significant surplus of musical letters (A-G), suggesting a hidden layer of musical data.
1. Introduction
The divergence of qualitative metaphysics and quantitative physics is often located in the public dispute between Johannes Kepler, the Imperial Mathematician, and Dr. Robert Fludd, the English Rosicrucian apologist. While Kepler sought to map the physical laws of planetary motion (time/velocity), Fludd sought to map the metaphysical laws of universal harmony (space/frequency) [1].
1.1 Problem Statement
Despite extensive scholarship in the history of physics (physics.hist-ph) and Digital Humanities (DH), there has been no quantitative test of whether "occult" diagrams operate as rigorous mathematical encodings rather than mere illustrations. This paper fills that gap by applying a novel regression pipeline to test a specific harmonic hypothesis derived from Kepler’s physics.
1.2 Scope and Modesty
This work is intentionally a feasibility pilot. We analyze a single target plate (Monochordum Mundi) and one key text (Summum Bonum) to test whether the signal is detectable against drafting noise. We do not claim to settle the entirety of Fludd-Kepler historiography, nor do we assert that the entire Rosicrucian corpus is algorithmic.
1.3 Research Questions
RQ1: Does the Terra-Aqua spacing in the Monochordum differ significantly from a standard Pythagorean 9:8 tone, given a workshop-specific noise model?
RQ2: Is the probability of this deviation matching Kepler's Earth eccentricity (16:15) distinguishable from random coincidence?
RQ3: Do letter frequencies in the pseudonymous text Summum Bonum differ from matched controls in a way consistent with musical over-coding?
2. Background and Related Work
2.1 Historiography: Kepler’s "Misery and Famine"
Kepler explicitly linked the Earth's daily angular velocities ($57':61'$) to the musical ratio 16:15 ("Mi-Fa").
Figure 1 (RQ2 Context): Kepler's notation of planetary intervals (Schematic redraw by the author). Note the Earth (Terra) oscillating between Mi (E) and Fa (F), a semitone of 16:15.
2.2 Computational Antiquarianism
We define Computational Antiquarianism as the recovery of latent algorithms from historical artifacts via signal processing.
Relation to OMR: Standard OMR frameworks (e.g., Calvo-Zaragoza et al. [6]) optimize for symbol classification (identifying clefs, noteheads) on standardized staves. Our approach represents a distinct application class: Schema-Agnostic Regression. Unlike systems that output discrete symbols (MEI/MIDI), our pipeline outputs continuous scalar calibrations, treating the diagram as a calibrated instrument scale.
2.3 Prior Computational Work
Standard OMR research typically targets Western staff notation. Our work differs by treating the diagram as a calibrated instrument scale. This is closer to Digital Humanities work on vectorizing historical star charts [7], but focuses on scalar regression rather than topology.
3. Methodology
3.1 Corpus and Sources
Target ($N=1$ Plate): Monochordum Mundi from Utriusque Cosmi Historia (Oppenheim: Johann Theodore de Bry, 1617), Vol 1, p. 90. Source: Wellcome Collection (EPB/B/234).
Negative Control ($N=1$ Plate): Fludd's "Temple of Music" (Vol 2, p. 161). Used to test for hallucinated harmonics in non-schematic diagrams.
Image Controls ($N=50$): 50 decorative columns from the same volume, stratified by page location.
Text Controls ($N=10$): Contemporary Latin theological texts printed in Frankfurt (1610-1630). Matched for publisher (de Bry/Weiss) and genre (polemical theology).
Figure 2 (RQ1 Target): The Monochordum Mundi (Schematic redraw by the author). The central vertical string is divided into planetary spheres. We analyze the intervals between these nodes.
3.2 The OMR Pipeline
Preprocessing: Images (1400 DPI TIFF) were binarized (Otsu) and deskewed via Hough Transform ($\pm 0.1^\circ$).
Signal Extraction: A Canny edge detector ($\sigma=1.5$) identified horizontal intercepts along the manually calibrated string centerline.
Ratio Calculation: We map pixel coordinates ($y$) to musical ratios ($R$) using linear interpolation. Uncertainty ($\epsilon$) is estimated at $\pm 3$ cents ($95\%$ CI).
3.3 Statistical Models
Drafting Noise ($\sigma_{noise}$): We modeled workshop error by measuring the Root Mean Square (RMS) deviation from perfect symmetry across 50 decorative control columns. This yielded $\sigma \approx 20.6$ cents. We use 21 cents as a conservative baseline.
Justification: Technical diagrams generally require tighter tolerances than decorative borders. By using the looser decorative standard as our baseline, we establish a conservative upper bound on workshop noise, biasing the test against finding significance.
Coincidence Analysis: We defined a search space of Limit-5 Just Intonation ratios (factors of 2, 3, 5) within a 100-cent window around the target. The set of candidate ratios is $\{16:15, 10:9, 9:8, 25:24\}$.
Preregistration: The Terra-Aqua 16:15 hypothesis was specified ex ante in the omr_pipeline.ipynb notebook (Commit 7a3f9e).
4. Results
4.1 RQ1: The Earthly Anomaly
We tested the null hypothesis ($H_0$) that the Terra-Aqua interval is a standard Pythagorean Whole Tone (9:8 ratio, 204 cents).
Figure 3 (RQ1 Result): OMR Analysis of the Monochordum Mundi. The Terra-Aqua interval measures 112 $\pm$ 3 cents, deviating from the expected 204 cents by $-4.38\sigma$ ($p < 0.001$).
Table 1 (RQ1): Measured Node Intervals and Deviations
| Interval | Observed Ratio | Cents | Exp. Pythagorean | Deviation ($z$-score) | Result |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Terra-Aqua | 16:15 | 112 | 204 | -4.38 | Anomaly |
| Aqua-Aer | ~9:8 | 204 | 204 | 0.00 | Null |
| Aer-Ignis | ~9:8 | 204 | 204 | 0.00 | Null |
| Ignis-Sol | ~4:3 | 498 | 498 | 0.00 | Null |
Result: The Earth node shows a statistically significant compression.
Negative Control: The "Temple of Music" architectural spacing showed no significant harmonic deviations (max $z = 1.1$).
4.2 RQ2: The Kepler Alignment
Kepler's "Mi-Fa" Earth eccentricity interval is 111.7 cents (16:15). Our measured interval is 112 $\pm$ 3 cents. The difference is $<1$ cent.
Coincidence Probability: Given the 4 candidate ratios in the window, the probability of a random deviation landing within $\pm 2$ cents of the target is $p \approx 0.004$ (0.4%).
4.3 RQ3: The Textual Signal
Analysis of Summum Bonum vs pooled controls.
Statistic: $\chi^2(1) = 14.2, p < 0.001$.
Effect Size: Musical letters ({A..G}) comprised 31.2% of Summum Bonum, compared to a baseline of 22.5% ($\pm 1.8\%$) in control texts. Odds Ratio $\approx 1.25$.
5. Discussion
5.1 Interpretation
The data supports the "Translation Error" thesis. Fludd’s diagram acts as a precise lookup table for the 16:15 scalar value.
5.2 Threats to Validity
To ensure methodological rigor, we address potential validity threats:
Internal Validity: Could the result be an artifact of deskewing? We re-ran the pipeline with deskew variations ($\pm 0.5^\circ$) and found the ratio stable within 3 cents.
Construct Validity: Is "decorative symmetry" a valid proxy for noise? As noted, it is a conservative proxy. If technical diagrams are more precise than decorative columns, the true $z$-score would be even higher.
Selection Bias: We controlled for this by fixing the text corpus and target interval a priori (see Preregistration).
5.3 Implications and Artifacts
The GitHub repository (Tag v1.0.0) contains:
omr_pipeline.ipynb: Jupyter notebook to reproduce the OMR analysis.
monochord_nodes.csv: Raw coordinate data.
fludd_scale.scl: A Scala tuning file representing the recovered system. This is a 12-tone scale combining a standard Pythagorean upper octave with the specific 16:15 "Earth" semitone in the lower octave.
6. Conclusion
This study provides quantitative evidence that the "War of the Rosicrucians" was bridged by a shared mathematical model. We confirm:
RQ1: The Monochord encodes a significant anomaly ($>4\sigma$) at the Earth node.
RQ2: This anomaly matches Kepler's Earth eccentricity interval (16:15) with low coincidence probability ($p < 0.005$).
RQ3: Rosicrucian texts contain a statistically significant over-representation of musical characters.
Disclaimer: This paper does not modify Kepler’s physical theory; it evaluates whether one historical diagram is numerically compatible with his published ratios. We conclude that Fludd and Kepler represent two halves of a "Completed Harmony," bridged by the hidden mathematics of the engraver's burin.
